[01]
name_jp = "ヒロシゲ36号 ～ Neo Super-Express"
name_en = "Hiroshige No.36 ~ Neo Super-Express"
comment8_en = "Though to Mary, the blond-haired girl, what she saw the extremely beautiful Japanesque scenery through Boyu Shinkansen Hiroshige was just a dull visual stimulation."
comment8_jp = "だが、この卯酉新幹線『ヒロシゲ』から見えている極めて日本的な美しい情景も、金髪の少女、メリーにとっては退屈な映像刺激でしかなかった。"
comment7_en = "Besides Mt.Fuji, even the sea coast on the left side is tremendously beautiful that isn't enough to be nominated as a world heritage a dozen of times. So beautiful is Tokaido."
comment7_jp = "富士どころか、左手に見える海岸だって、世界遺産に一ダースほど認定されてもまだ足りないくらい美しい。東海道はこんなにも美しいのだ。"
comment6_en = "Because of the effort of Mount Fuji Revival Association, Mt.Fuji has finally been nominated as a world heritage, while the one you see from Hiroshige looks much sacred.\nOne of the reason is that from the panoramic view of Hiroshige, you'll never see any high buildings, power transmission lines or overhead wires."
comment6_jp = "富士山復興会の努力により、近年になって漸く世界遺産に認定された富士だが、ヒロシゲから見えているこの富士の方が何倍も荘厳に見える。\nというのも、ヒロシゲのパノラマビューから見ると、高層ビルも送電線も高架線も何一つ見つけられないのも一つの理由だろう。"
comment5_en = "It may be having passed for 25 minutes after leaving... In the far distance the Mount Fuji covered with clouds has shown up.\nIt looks sacred as if a wizard lives there."
comment5_jp = "出発から25分ほど経っただろうか、遠くに雲の傘を被った富士の山が見えた。\nまるで仙人でも住んでいそうな厳かな姿をしている。"
comment4_en = "A warm and mild spring sunshine came from the windows. This newest type of shinkansen features a half-panoramic view in all the cars. The half-panoramic view is as if a test tube is running on the railway. They're all windows except up and down, in other words, the walls of the shinkansen are almost the windows.\nThe left side of a blond-haired girl sitting against the running direction was a beautiful blue sea coast; the right side was awesome plain with no buildings and pine wood."
comment4_jp = "車窓から春の陽気が入ってくる。最新型のこの新幹線は全車両、半パノラマビューが一つの売りである。半パノラマビューとは上下を除いた全てが窓、つまり新幹線の壁は殆ど窓で、まるで大きなガラスの試験管が線路の上を走っている様な物だ。\n進行方向と反対に座っている金髪の少女の左手には、見渡す限りの美しい青の海岸、右手には建物一つ無い美しい平原と松林が広がっていた。"
comment3_en = "There were plenty of vacant box-shaped seats for up to four persons, so even if you two sat there, nobody will sit with you. The opposite direction in the morning is extremely crowded by commuters, while this direction for Tokyo is vacant. It was good for them."
comment3_jp = "四人まで座れるボックス型の席には空きも多く見られ、二人で座っていたとしても相席を求められる事は無かった。朝の反対方向は芋洗いの様に通勤の人でごった返すが、東京行きは空いている。二人にとっては好都合だった。"
comment2_en = "Hiroshige runs for the east, which is two girls inside. It runs for the east, with no noise or no swing."
comment2_jp = "ヒロシゲは二人を乗せて東へ走る。音もなく、揺れもなく、ただひたすら東に走る。"

[02]
name_jp = "53ミニッツの青い海"
name_en = "Blue Sea of 53 Minutes"
comment10_en = "Also, what it made people amaze is that the Shinkansen runs straight without any curves under the ground. From the first station to the last one, you cannot see any sky, sea, mountain, forest, the Sun or the Moon."
comment10_jp = "驚くべき事に、卯酉新幹線の全てが地下に、そして直線的に作られている。始点から終点まで、空も海も、山も森も、太陽も月も、何も見ることは出来ないのだ。"
comment9_en = "After that, Boyu Shinkansen Hiroshige was born. It runs between Kyoto and Tokyo in 53 minutes. This Shinkansen enabled the commuters to come and go between Kyoto and Tokyo, and it became the main traffic infrastructure of Japan all of a sudden."
comment9_jp = "そして完成したのが、京都―東京間を53分で繋ぐ卯酉新幹線『ヒロシゲ』である。この新幹線は、京都―東京を通勤圏内にし、あっという間に日本の大動脈となった。"
comment8_en = "After the Jinki removal of the capital, many people faced with the necessity of coming and going Tokyo and Kyoto. Suddenly only the former Tokaido Shinkansen hadn't been enough to solve the situation, so the government started developing a new Shinkansen as soon as they could."
comment8_jp = "神亀の遷都が行われてから、大量の人間が東京と京都を行き来する必要が生まれた。旧東海道だけではすぐに交通インフラに限界が来て、政府は急ピッチに新しい新幹線の開発に取りかかったのだ。"
comment7_en = "   ...It was before they were born that Boyu Tokaido had started an operation."
comment7_jp = "   ――卯酉東海道が出来たのは、二人が生まれる前の事である。"
comment6_en = "   \"I'm a celebrity.\""
comment6_jp = "   「セレブですわ」"
comment5_en = "      \"How luxurious. Nowadays, those who take on it are only people from the northeast, Indians and celebrities.\n      I reckon you're as carefree as people in Tohoku.\""
comment5_jp = "      「何を贅沢言ってるのよ。旧東海道なんて、もう東北人とインド人とセレブくらいしか利用していないわよ。\n      ま、メリーは東北人並にのんびりしているかも知れないけどね」"
comment4_en = "   \"I don't think Mt.Fuji on the ground is more beautiful than that in the underground, still I wanted to see the genuine one.\n   I wish I took on the former Tokaido Shinkansen.\""
comment4_jp = "   「地上の富士はここまで綺麗じゃないかも知れないけど、それでも本物の方が見たかったわ。\n   これなら旧東海道新幹線の方が良かったなぁ」"
comment3_en = "      \"You say so, but it's more brighter than the subway in past days. It's because the picture on the tunnels.\n      Feels like we're on the ground, don't we?\""
comment3_jp = "      「これでもトンネルに映像が流れるようになって、昔の地下鉄よりは明るくなったのよ。\n      まるで地上みたいでしょ？」"
comment2_en = "   \"Hiroshige has large seats and runs very quickly, so it's convenient...\n   But to me, it's dull to see just a 'fake' scenery through Kaleido-screen.\""
comment2_jp = "   「ヒロシゲは席は広いし、早く着くし便利なんだけど――\n   カレイドスクリーンの『偽物の』景色しか見られないのは退屈ねぇ」"

[03]
name_jp = "竹取飛翔　～ Lunatic Princess"
name_en = "Flight of the Bamboo Cutter ~ Lunatic Princess"
comment10_en = "That's the ultimate feature of Boyu Tokaido that cost a fortune. The device is called Kaleido-screen."
comment10_jp = "それが、卯酉東海道最大の売りと予算を使った装置『カレイドスクリーン』だった。"
comment9_en = "In spite of it, the train presented them the sunlight from the windows like that on the ground in the afternoon and displayed the beautiful Mt.Fuji and Pacific Ocean."
comment9_jp = "それでも、昼間の外と同じくらいの光が窓から射し、そして外には美しい富士と太平洋が映し出されていた。"
comment8_en = "She was also looking forward to the scenery on the way to Tokyo, but unfortunately, all of Boyu Tokaido are the shinkansen that run under the ground."
comment8_jp = "道中の景色も楽しみだったのだが、あいにく卯酉新幹線は全線完全地下の新幹線である。"
comment7_en = "Renko Usami and Maribel Han (Mary) decided to make a trip to Tokyo where Renko's parents live during the vacation of university.\nIt was just a trip for Mary to follow a Renko's visit for Higan, still she was looking forward to this trip so much. It's because she's never been to Tokyo."
comment7_jp = "宇佐見蓮子とマエリベリー・ハーン（メリー）の二人は、大学の休みを利用して、蓮子の実家である東京へ旅行する事になった。\n旅行と言っても蓮子の彼岸参りに便乗するだけだが、まだ東京に行った事が無いメリーは、今回の東京旅行を非常に楽しみにしていた。"
comment6_en = "   \"One night per minute. With such a pace, I'd be weak getting old in three weeks. What a short journey it is...\""
comment6_jp = "   「一分一泊ね。その調子なら三週間で老衰だわ。短い旅ねぇ」"
comment5_en = "      \"Have you heard this story?\n      To tell the truth, Hiroshige would run less than 53 minutes with its maximum speed, yet they've expressly adjusted to run in 53 minutes sharp.\""
comment5_jp = "      「そうそう、こんな話知ってる？\n      実は、ヒロシゲは最高速を出せば53分も掛からないらしいんだけど、わざわざ 53分になる様に調整したらしいよ？」"
comment4_en = "   \"Ah, yes. You're right.\n   Oh dear, can I see the ancient rabbits making a medicine on the fake full moon?\""
comment4_jp = "   「はいはい、そうですね。\n   あーあ、偽物の満月には、太古の兎が薬を搗いている姿が見えるのかなぁ」"
comment3_en = "      \"Though the time being in a train have become shorter, you can still call it a journey. The sightseeing in Tokyo is such fun.\n      There're plenty of historic-taste buildings in Shinjuku, Shibuya and so on which aren't in Kyoto.\n      You'd feel better if you thought you got time for visiting there.\""
comment3_jp = "      「道中が短くなっただけで、旅行は旅行よ。東京観光巡りは面白いわよ？\n      京都と違って新宿とか渋谷とかには歴史を感じる建物も多いしね。\n      そういう観光の時間が増えたと思えば良いじゃない」"
comment2_en = "   \"It's nice to arrive in a moment, but aren't you bored with such a fake scenery, Renko?\n   I cannot be satisfied with the fake full moon floating up in the night sky, too.\n   In the past Tokaido had 53 stations, while now, it only takes 53 minutes in spite of the longer way than that of the old days.\n   You have no way to call it a journey anymore.\""
comment2_jp = "   「あっという間に着くのは良いけど、こんな偽物の景色を見てるだけじゃ蓮子は退屈じゃないの？\n   夜は夜で空に浮かぶのは偽物の満月、ってのもなんかねぇ。\n   東海道も昔は53も宿場町があったというのに、今は53分で着いちゃうのよ？　昔よりも道のりも長いのに、\n   こうなっちゃうと、もう旅とは呼べないわよねぇ」"
comment11_jp = "(『東方文花帖』の『幻想の音覚』より)\n未だ、実際にこの眼でかぐや姫を見たことがない私は、竹取物語を読んで想像するしかなく、私なりな解釈で竹取物語終了後を曲にしてみました。\n満月の夜に現れる月の使者、それに抵抗する地上の人間。だが月の死者の前では為す術もなくやられてしまう。もう抵抗する気も失ったその時、地上の竹が光り始めて……現われたのは月の姫、かぐや姫だった。かぐやはこれ以上人間には迷惑をかけまいと、一人戦う決心をしたのである。\nという妄想は無く、大昔の日本の空にあったと言われる月と、空を翔る姫達をイメージして作曲しました。勿論遊び心も忘れずに、判る人だけに判るレトロさを入れて、何十年後になったときに最後まで心に残る曲になるよう頑張りました。"
comment11_en = "(Bohemian Archive in Japanese Red Music Columns)\nWhile I am someone who has yet to actually see Kaguya-hime, this song was not meant to represent The Tale of the Bamboo Cutter, but rather what happens after the story ends.\nThe messengers from the moon who reveal themselves only on nights of the full moon, and the ones they oppose, the humans on Earth. But those from the moon reach their wits' end and lose the will to fight. That's when the bamboo on Earth begins to glow... and the moon princess appears, that is, Kaguya-hime. Kaguya troubles the humans, and one man decides to fight her.\nMy image for this song is nothing that off-the-wall. It's more of the moon that was said to exist in Japan's sky a long time ago, and the princesses that fly through that sky. Of course, they still haven't lost their playful spirit, just like how some people still enjoy retro games. As I also want my songs to remain in people's minds decades from now, I will continue to do my best."

